06073nam a22008895i 9780231526975DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2011049965  a(OCoLC)979574945  a97802315269757 a10.7312/flyn153582doi  a(DE-B1597)458857  a(OCoLC)812924902  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPN1995.9.T67bS37 2012 4aPN1995.9.T67bS37 2015 7aSOC0040002bisacsh04a791.4363522231 aFlynn, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aScreening Torture :bMedia Representations of State Terror and Political Domination /cMichael Flynn, Fabiola Fernandez Salek. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b‹B›Color Photos: ‹/B›17.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tScreening Torture -- tPart I: Torture and the Implications of Masculinity -- t1. Countering the Jack Bauer Effect -- t2. Mel Gibson’s Tortured Heroes -- t3. It’s a Perfect World -- tPart II: Torture and the Sadomasochistic Impulse -- t4. Lust, Caution -- t5. The Art of Photogenic Torture -- t6. Beyond Susan Sontag -- t7. Stanley Kubrick’s A Clockwork Orange as Art Against Torture -- tPart III: Confronting the Legacies of Torture and State Terror -- t8. “Accorded a Place in the Design” -- t9. Confessing Without Regret -- tPART IV: Torture and the Shortcomings of Film -- t10. Movies of Modern Torture as Convenient Truths -- t11. Torture at the Limit of Politics -- t12. Doing Torture in Film -- t13. Documenting the Documentaries on Abu Ghraib -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBefore 9/11, films addressing torture outside of the horror/slasher genre depicted the practice in a variety of forms. In most cases, torture was cast as the act of a desperate and depraved individual, and the viewer was more likely to identify with the victim rather than the torturer. Since the terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001, scenes of brutality and torture in mainstream comedies, dramatic narratives, and action films appear for little other reason than to titillate and delight. In these films, torture is devoid of any redeeming qualities, represented as an exercise in brutal senselessness carried out by authoritarian regimes and institutions.This volume follows the shift in the representation of torture over the past decade, specifically in documentary, action, and political films. It traces and compares the development of this trend in films from the United States, Europe, China, Latin America, South Africa, and the Middle East. Featuring essays by sociologists, psychologists, historians, journalists, and specialists in film and cultural studies, the collection approaches the representation of torture in film and television from multiple angles and disciplines, connecting its aesthetics and practices to the dynamic of state terror and political domination.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aTorture in motion pictures. 0aTorture on television. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh1 aAlexander, Livia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarney, Phil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDanzig, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDevji, Faisal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFernandez Salek, Fabiola, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aFlynn, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLazreg, Marnia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCoy, Alfred W., econtributor.4ctb4ht